e relations with the Soviets. In the face of governmental apathy, activists in the United States hatched a bold plan: unite Jewish Americans to demand that Washington exert pressure on Moscow for change.A Cold War Exodus delves into the gripping narrative of how these men and women, through ingenuity and determination, devised mass mobilization tactics during a three-decade-long campaign to liberate Soviet Jews—an endeavor that would ultimately lead to one of the most significant mass emigrations in Jewish history.Drawing from a wealth of archival sources including the travelogues of thousands of American tourists who smuggled aid to Russian Jews, Shaul Kelner offers a compelling tale of activism and its profound impact, revealing how a seemingly disparate array of elements could be woven together to forge a movement and achieve the seemingly impossible. It is a testament to the power of unity, creativity, and the unwavering dedication of those who believe in the cause of human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican Jews.  aUSSR.  aactivism.  abooks about the cold war.  acold war history.  acold war.  ahuman rights.  ajewish book.  ajewish history book.  ajewish history.  ajewish studies.  ajewish.  ajews in America.  ajews in the soviet union.  ajews.  amass emigration.  amoscow.  arussia.  asociology.  asoviet jews.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479872800.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479872800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479872800/original  a978-3-11-075164-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-a